ons these icons promote for addressing global injustice, when examined critically, can be seen to work through the very same institutions that create these problems in the first place.This volume assesses the growing role of popular icons in the construction of a culture that appears to incorporate a critical attitude towards the capitalist experience while, in fact, legitimizing the neoliberal character of the modern world. It will be an eye-opening read for anyone interested in the juncture between current events and celebrity culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCapitalism. 0aCelebritiesxPolitical activity. 0aCelebrities. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPhilanthropists. 0aSocial change. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Advocacy.2bisacsh1 aBaban, Feyzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErvine, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFridell, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFridell, Gavin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodman, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapoor, Ilan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonings, Martijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonings, Martijn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Manique, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeck, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRahman, Momin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442696228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442696228.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKA